SIMPLE: incurable
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Incurable
<hw>In*cur"a*ble</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>incurable</ets>, L. <ets>incurabilis</ets>. See <er>In-</er> not,
and <er>Curable</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Not capable of being cured; beyond the power of
skill or medicine to remedy; <as>as, an <ex>incurable</ex>
disease</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A scirrhus is not absolutely <qex>incurable</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Arbuthnot.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Not admitting or capable of remedy or correction;
irremediable; remediless; <as>as, <ex>incurable</ex>
evils</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Rancorous and <qex>incurable</qex> hostility.</q>
<rj><qau>Burke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They were laboring under a profound, and, as it might have seemed,
an almost <qex>incurable</qex> ignorance.</q> <rj><qau>Sir J.
Stephen.</qau></rj></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Irremediable; remediless; irrecoverable;
irretrievable; irreparable; hopeless.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Incurable</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Incurable
<hw>In*cur"a*ble</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A person diseased beyond
cure.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Incurableness</ent>⟦br⟧
